          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In production API pipelines, OCR latency can silently degrade user experience and system throughput, particularly in applications like real-time document verification or high-volume data extraction. When milliseconds matter, choosing a model engineered for speed is critical. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets OCR S",
            "bold": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " model, specifically the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets_Ocr_S_F16",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " variant, is designed to deliver low-latency inference without sacrificing accuracy, making it a strong candidate for latency-sensitive deployments."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This post dives into the practical aspects of optimizing "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets OCR S latency",
            "bold": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". You'll find detailed performance characteristics, step-by-step integration guides, real-world use cases, and troubleshooting tips—all tailored for experienced API teams. By the end, you'll have a clear roadmap to achieve consistent, fast OCR responses in your production stack."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Performance Characteristics of Nanonets OCR S"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Understanding the baseline latency of Nanonets OCR S is essential for setting realistic expectations and identifying optimization opportunities. In controlled tests, the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets_Ocr_S_F16",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " model typically processes standard document images (e.g., 1024x768 pixels) in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "120-180 milliseconds",
            "bold": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " under moderate API load. This includes network round-trip time when deployed in the same region as the client. Key factors influencing latency include image resolution, document complexity, and concurrent request volume."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h3",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Benchmark Results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Internal benchmarks reveal that latency scales linearly with image size but remains efficient due to the model's F16 quantization. For instance, processing a 2048x1536 image may take "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "250-300 ms",
            "bold": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", while smaller thumbnails (512x512) can drop to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "80-100 ms",
            "bold": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". These numbers assume optimal conditions: a stable network connection and no API rate limiting. It's crucial to monitor these metrics in your environment, as real-world latency can vary based on infrastructure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To measure latency accurately, instrument your API calls with high-resolution timers. Avoid relying solely on server-side logs, as network jitter can add variability. Tools like "
          },
          {
            "type": "a",
            "url": "https://prometheus.io/",
            "title": null,
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Prometheus"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for metrics collection can help track p95 and p99 latencies, ensuring you catch outliers that impact user experience."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Integration Steps for Low-Latency Deployments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Integrating Nanonets OCR S with latency in mind requires careful client configuration. Start by using the official SDK or a lightweight HTTP client to minimize overhead. Ensure your requests are asynchronous where possible to avoid blocking threads, and implement connection pooling to reduce TCP handshake delays."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Here's a Python example demonstrating a low-latency API call with timing instrumentation:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "lang": "python",
        "value": "import requests\nimport time\n\nAPI_KEY = \"your_api_key\"\nENDPOINT = \"https://api.nanonets.com/v2/ocr/s\"\n\nheaders = {\"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {API_KEY}\"}\nfiles = {\"file\": open(\"document.jpg\", \"rb\")}\n\nstart_time = time.perf_counter()\nresponse = requests.post(ENDPOINT, headers=headers, files=files)\nlatency = (time.perf_counter() - start_time) * 1000  # Convert to ms\n\nprint(f\"Latency: {latency:.2f} ms\")\nprint(f\"Response: {response.json()}\")",
